ODE XVIII.

A thn to Faunus; cp. 1. 17. 1—8. Horace prays that the visits of the god to his lands may be kindly, and promises that the due kid and wine and incense shall be offered at the Faunalia on the nones of December, ,the holiday of cattle and of villagers, the day of peace, when even the wolf strays hannlessly among the lambs 3 when the trees shed their leaves to strew F aunus’ path, and the ditcher revenges himself on the ground which has worked him so hard, by dancing on it.
